995. Eheu, quom. Mil. 1358 Eheu, quom uenit mi in mentem, ut mores mutandi sient, Poen. 791 Eheu, quom 690 habui hariolos haruspices. So ei mila· quom Men. 304, Ter. Andr. 622. On the Mood, see note on V. 151. Plus minusque is usually changed by editors to plus minusue, the form in which the phrase occurs (in a different context) in Ter. Plzorm. 554 Ne quid plus minusue faxit, quod nos post pz'yeat, Geta. Another form appears in Men. 592 Aut plus aut minus quam opus fuerat dicto dixeram controuersiam, in the sense of ‘about,⁷ ‘nearly.' Here plus minusque of the MSS. should be retained. Hegio had done both too much evil and too little good to his son. Quam me aequom fuit. The loss of me in the MSS. between quam and ‹leqzlom is so natural, that we ean hardly resist the accepted restoration of the metre of the line. At the same time Aul. 424 minas quam ae'cstlom erat feel offers the phrase in the same form with (apparently) legitimate hiatus after quam. Fuit is the Past Tense of that est which is normal in the phrase (nequem est, ‘it would be just? Cf. Mero. 81 odio me esse quoi placere aequom fuit, Mil. 725 aequom fuit Deos palmulam, 'nno exemplo ne omnes uitam uiuerent. Fuerat however often takes its place, eg. Τνίη. 119 Εἰ rei operam dare te fuerat aliquanto aequius, Si qul probiorem facere posses. (See note on v. 17.)

997. Ornatus haud ex suis uirtutibus. This was apparently a current phrase, for it recurs in Ter. Adel. 176:

A. regnumne, Aeschine, hic tu possides? R. Si possiderem, ornatus esses ex tuis uirtutibus.
